  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Proprioceptive weighting changes may explain differences in postural control performance. In
      addition, the respiratory movement has a disturbing effect on postural balance. Postural
      balance seems to be impaired in individuals with respiratory disorders. Increased risk of
      falling is reported in individuals with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Besides the
      essential role of respiration, the diaphragm may also play an important role in the control
      of the trunk and postural balance.

      The aim of the study is to clarify whether proprioceptive postural control is impaired in
      individuals with diaphragm paresis.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
